OCP-AI MetalLB + CNPG Troubleshooting Walkthrough
March 31, 2026

Problem: MetalLB L2 VIP services on VLAN interfaces (bnd0.1794/1797/1798) not reachable cross-node or externally. 7 LoadBalancer services across dev/test/prod all timing out.

Troubleshooting approach: Start at L2 and work up. If L2 is fine, check L3/iptables. The idea is to narrow down where the packet is getting lost by tracing it through each stage — MetalLB → ARP → ingress → DNAT → routing → egress. At each step, if it looks good, move to the next. If something's off, dig into that layer.


1. Verify MetalLB is assigning IPs and speakers are advertising

oc get svc -A --field-selector spec.type=LoadBalancer
oc get pods -n metallb-system
oc logs -n metallb-system -l component=speaker --tail=50 | grep -i "announce\|arp\|layer2"

What to look for: MetalLB speaker logs should show it sending gratuitous ARPs for each VIP. If it's not advertising, check L2Advertisement and IPAddressPool resources.

Example good log (speaker is advertising):
  {"msg":"sending gratuitous ARP","interface":"bnd0.1794","ip":"10.172.194.160","event":"arpReply"}

Example bad log (speaker can't advertise):
  {"msg":"no usable address found on interface","interface":"bnd0.1794"}

In our case: MetalLB was fine — speakers were advertising, ARPs were going out, IPs were assigned. The problem was never MetalLB itself.

Why check this first: It's the most common cause of LB not working — MetalLB misconfigured, wrong pool, speaker not running on the right node, L2Advertisement not matching the pool. Eliminates the obvious stuff fast.


2. Check ARP — is the VIP resolving to the right MAC?

From the workstation:
arping -c 3 10.172.194.160

From inside the cluster (oc debug):
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host arping -c 3 -I bnd0.1794 10.172.194.160

What to look for: ARP replies should come back with the MAC of the node that owns the VIP. If ARP works but traffic still times out, the problem is routing not L2.

In our case: ARP worked perfectly — VIPs resolved to the correct node MAC. Packets were arriving at the node but getting lost after that. This told us it was a routing/filtering problem, not an L2 problem.

Why check this next: If MetalLB is advertising but nc still times out, either the packet isn't reaching the node (L2/ARP issue) or it's reaching the node and getting lost (L3/routing). ARP check tells you which one. If ARP works, the packet IS arriving — so the problem is on the node itself.


3. Check if DNAT rules exist for the VIP

oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host iptables -t nat -L OVN-KUBE-EXTERNALIP -n --line-numbers

What to look for: DNAT rules mapping the VIP to the ClusterIP. These should exist on ALL nodes (not just the one that owns the VIP), in both PREROUTING and OUTPUT chains. OVN creates these.

In our case: DNAT rules existed on all nodes. OVN was creating them correctly. The DNAT itself was firing — we confirmed by watching the counter increment. The issue was what happened AFTER the DNAT.

Why check this next: Packet is arriving at the node (ARP works) but the service isn't responding. OVN-Kubernetes uses DNAT rules in the OVN-KUBE-EXTERNALIP chain to redirect VIP traffic to the ClusterIP. If those rules don't exist, the node receives the packet but has no idea what to do with it. Checking DNAT tells you whether OVN even knows about the VIP.


4. Trace the packet path through iptables

Add a LOG rule in raw PREROUTING to see if packets arrive at all:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host iptables -t raw -I PREROUTING -d 10.172.194.160 -j LOG --log-prefix "RAW-PRE: "

Then test:
nc -zv 10.172.194.160 9000

Check dmesg for the log:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host dmesg | grep RAW-PRE | tail -5

What to look for: IN=bnd0.1794 means the packet arrived on the VLAN interface. If you see it in raw but DNAT counters don't increment, something between raw and nat is dropping it.

Example dmesg output (packet arriving):
  [12345.678] RAW-PRE: IN=bnd0.1794 OUT= MAC=00:25:b5:50:0a:67:7c:8c:09:c3:74:1e:08:00 SRC=10.172.248.105 DST=10.172.194.160 PROTO=TCP DPT=9000

Key fields: IN= tells you which interface the packet arrived on, SRC= is the client, DST= is the VIP.

In our case: RAW-PRE LOG fired every time — packets were definitely arriving at the node. This confirmed L2 was fine and the problem was somewhere in the iptables/routing stack after packet ingress.

Why check this next: DNAT rules exist and counters say they're firing, but the service still doesn't respond. So the packet arrives, gets DNAT'd, but something happens after that. Adding a LOG in raw PREROUTING (the very first thing the kernel processes) gives you definitive proof the packet is hitting the node — if the LOG doesn't fire, the packet never arrived and it's a switch/VLAN/L2 issue. If it does fire, the problem is further down the stack.


5. After DNAT — where does the packet go?

The key question: after OUTPUT or PREROUTING DNAT rewrites the destination to the ClusterIP, which interface does the packet exit through?

Add LOG in POSTROUTING:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host iptables -t nat -I POSTROUTING -m conntrack --ctstate DNAT -j LOG --log-prefix "POST-DNAT: "

What to look for: Check the OUT= field in dmesg. If it says OUT=br-ex, the packet is going into OVN (correct). If it says OUT=bnd0.1794, the policy routing table is sending it back out the VLAN interface instead of into OVN (this was our bug).

What we saw (bad — packet exiting the wrong interface):
  [12345.789] POST-DNAT: IN= OUT=bnd0.1794 SRC=10.172.248.105 DST=172.30.161.228 PROTO=TCP DPT=9000

Notice DST is now 172.30.x.x (ClusterIP — DNAT worked) but OUT=bnd0.1794 (wrong — should be br-ex). The policy routing table sent it out the VLAN gateway.

What it should look like after fix:
  [12345.789] POST-DNAT: IN= OUT=br-ex SRC=10.172.248.105 DST=172.30.161.228 PROTO=TCP DPT=9000

In our case: This was the breakthrough moment. Seeing OUT=bnd0.1794 instead of OUT=br-ex told us the kernel was routing the DNAT'd packet back out the VLAN interface. That pointed straight at the policy routing tables.

Why check this next: We know the packet arrives (step 4) and gets DNAT'd (step 3). But the service still doesn't respond, which means the DNAT'd packet isn't making it to the actual pod. On OVN-Kubernetes, DNAT'd traffic needs to enter OVN via br-ex. Putting a LOG in POSTROUTING shows you exactly where the packet is going AFTER DNAT. The OUT= field is the smoking gun — it tells you which interface the kernel chose as the exit path.


6. Policy routing tables — the root cause

Check what's in the policy routing tables:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip rule show
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip route show table 100
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip route show table 101
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip route show table 102

Example output BEFORE fix (missing ClusterIP route):
  default via 10.172.194.1 dev bnd0.1794
  10.172.194.0/23 dev bnd0.1794 scope link src 10.172.194.151

Example output AFTER fix:
  default via 10.172.194.1 dev bnd0.1794
  10.172.194.0/23 dev bnd0.1794 scope link src 10.172.194.151
  172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex    <-- this is what was missing

What to look for: Tables 100/101/102 correspond to VLANs 1794/1797/1798. NMState creates them with source-based routing — any traffic with a source IP on that VLAN subnet gets routed through that table. The tables originally only had a default gateway via the VLAN interface. After DNAT rewrites the dest to a ClusterIP (172.30.x.x), the packet hits the policy table (because the source IP is still on the VLAN subnet), finds no route to 172.30.0.0/16, and sends it out the default gateway — wrong.

Fix: add ClusterIP route to each table:
ip route add 172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex table 100
ip route add 172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex table 101
ip route add 172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex table 102

169.254.0.4 is the OVN gateway router on br-ex.

Why check this next: Step 5 showed OUT=bnd0.1794, which means the kernel chose to route the packet out the VLAN interface instead of br-ex. On Linux, if you have policy routing rules (ip rule show), traffic can get routed through a different table than the main one. NMState creates these tables for source-based routing on the VLAN interfaces. So the question becomes: what's in those tables and why is it sending ClusterIP-destined traffic out the wrong interface?

In our case: All three tables (100/101/102) had the same problem — only a default route via the VLAN gateway and no route to the ClusterIP range. NMState set these up for source-based routing which is correct for normal storage traffic, but it doesn't account for DNAT'd MetalLB traffic that needs to reach OVN. After adding the 172.30.0.0/16 route, VLAN 1794 services immediately started working. VLANs 1797 and 1798 were still broken — that turned out to be rp_filter (step 8).


7. MASQUERADE — needed for return traffic

Even with the route fix, OVN needs the source IP to be something it knows about. DNAT'd packets arriving on br-ex still have the external client's source IP. OVN doesn't know how to route the reply back. Need a MASQUERADE rule:

iptables -t nat -I POSTROUTING -m conntrack --ctstate DNAT -o br-ex -j MASQUERADE

This rewrites the source to the node's br-ex IP so OVN can handle the return path.

Why this was needed: Once the routing fix got packets into OVN via br-ex, we still weren't getting responses. The packet entered OVN with the external client's source IP, but OVN only knows about pod and service IPs. It doesn't know how to route a reply back to an external IP like 10.172.248.105. MASQUERADE makes OVN think the traffic came from the node itself, and conntrack handles mapping the reply back to the real client.

In our case: Without MASQUERADE, the DNAT'd packet arrived on br-ex with the external client's source IP (e.g., 10.172.248.105). OVN had no idea how to send the reply back to that IP since it's not part of the pod or service network. MASQUERADE rewrites the source to the node's br-ex IP so the reply goes back to the node, which then forwards it back to the client via conntrack. The MASQUERADE counter confirmed it was working once we got the routing right.


8. rp_filter — the silent killer

After fixing routing for VLAN 1794, VLANs 1797 and 1798 still timed out. Packets arrived (raw PREROUTING LOG fired) but got dropped before nat.

Check rp_filter:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host sysctl -a | grep "rp_filter" | grep bnd0

Example output (bad — filtering enabled):
  net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1794.rp_filter = 1
  net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1797.rp_filter = 1
  net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1798.rp_filter = 1

Example output (good — filtering disabled):
  net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1794.rp_filter = 0
  net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1797.rp_filter = 0
  net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1798.rp_filter = 0

What to look for: rp_filter=1 means strict reverse path filtering. If a packet arrives on bnd0.1797 from source 10.172.194.x (a different subnet), the kernel checks "would I route a reply to 10.172.194.x back out bnd0.1797?" — no, it would use bnd0.1794. Packet silently dropped.

Fix:
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1794.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1797.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1798.rp_filter=0

Note: sysctl uses / instead of . for interface names (bnd0/1794 not bnd0.1794).

Why check this next: VLAN 1794 started working after the policy route and MASQUERADE fixes, but 1797 and 1798 still timed out. Same exact setup, same fixes applied, but only 1794 works? That means something else is dropping packets specifically on 1797/1798. The RAW-PRE LOG still fired on those VLANs, so the packet IS arriving. But the DNAT counter wasn't incrementing — meaning the packet is getting dropped between raw and nat. There aren't many things that sit between raw PREROUTING and nat PREROUTING. Connection tracking (conntrack) and rp_filter are the main suspects. Since conntrack was fine (it was working for 1794), rp_filter was the next thing to check.

In our case: This was the second bug. After the policy routing fix, VLAN 1794 worked but 1797 and 1798 still timed out. Packets were arriving (RAW-PRE LOG confirmed it) but vanishing before nat PREROUTING could process them. Turning off rp_filter on all bnd0.* interfaces on all nodes immediately fixed 1797 and 1798. The reason: external clients from the plnx-admin workstation (10.172.248.x) were hitting VIPs on bnd0.1797 and bnd0.1798, but the kernel's reverse path check said "I wouldn't route a reply to 10.172.248.x via bnd0.1797" and silently dropped the packet. No log, no counter, nothing — completely silent.


9. Validation — all 7 VIPs

for ip_port in 10.172.194.160:9000 10.172.194.161:19530 10.172.194.163:5432 \
               10.172.198.160:9000 10.172.198.161:19530 \
               10.172.202.160:9000 10.172.202.161:19530 10.172.202.163:5432; do
  echo -n "Testing $ip_port: "
  nc -zv ${ip_port%:*} ${ip_port#*:} 2>&1 | tail -1
done


10. Making it permanent — MachineConfig

All the fixes need to survive reboots. Created two MachineConfigs (master + worker) with:
- /etc/sysctl.d/99-metallb-rp-filter.conf — disables rp_filter on bnd0.* interfaces
- /etc/NetworkManager/dispatcher.d/99-metallb-vlan-routing — runs on bnd0.* interface up, sets rp_filter=0 and adds ClusterIP route to the right policy table
- /usr/local/bin/metallb-vlan-routing-setup.sh — systemd oneshot at boot, adds MASQUERADE rule, sets rp_filter, adds ClusterIP routes to tables 100/101/102
- metallb-vlan-routing.service — runs the setup script after OVS and NetworkManager are up

MachineConfigs pushed to ArgoCD repo: 99-metallb-vlan-routing-master and 99-metallb-vlan-routing-worker.

Important MachineConfig gotchas:
- Must use Ignition 3.5.0 (not 3.2.0 — wrong version causes RenderDegraded)
- File modes must be decimal (493 = 0755, 420 = 0644)
- File contents must be base64 data URI, not inline


CNPG Recovery

During the MachineConfig rollout, MCO drained master01. CNPG tried switching PostgreSQL primary from db-1 (on master01) to db-2. Switchover got stuck.

What happened:
- db-1 pod evicted from master01
- db-2 couldn't promote — stuck replaying WAL from MinIO archive
- WAL files in MinIO had system identifier 7621790087615889432
- db-2's pg_control had system identifier 7623307342724771863
- Mismatch = WAL from a previous/different cluster instance
- db-2 kept looping: restore WAL from MinIO → mismatch → try streaming replication → connection refused → wait → repeat

How to check:
oc logs pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod --tail=100 | grep -iE "wal|system identifier|recover|promot"

The stuck loop looks like this (repeating every ~5 seconds):
  {"msg":"Restored WAL file","walName":"000000010000000000000035","elapsedWalTime":0.309}
  {"message":"restored log file \"000000010000000000000035\" from archive"}
  {"message":"WAL file is from different database system: WAL file database system identifier is 7621790087615889432, pg_control database system identifier is 7623307342724771863"}
  {"message":"streaming replication receiver \"pai-apps-db\" could not connect to the primary server: connection to server at \"pai-apps-db-rw\" (172.30.138.226), port 5432 failed: Connection refused"}
  {"message":"waiting for WAL to become available at 0/35000078"}

The key line is "WAL file is from different database system" — that tells you the WAL archive in MinIO is from a different PostgreSQL instance than what's running.

When CNPG status shows stuck:
kubectl cnpg status pai-apps-db -n pai-prod

  Instances status
  Name           Current LSN  Replication role  Status         Node
  pai-apps-db-1  -            -                 InternalError  ocp-ai-master01.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-2  -            -                 InternalError  ocp-ai-master02.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-3  -            -                 InternalError  ocp-ai-master03.calix.local

All instances showing InternalError with no LSN means no primary is up. The error detail will say something like:
  "failed to connect to `user=postgres database=postgres`: server error: FATAL: the database system is starting up (SQLSTATE 57P03)"

After recovery, healthy output looks like:
  Name           Current LSN  Replication role      Status  Node
  pai-apps-db-2  0/3A026238   Primary               OK      ocp-ai-master02.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-1  0/3A026238   Standby (file based)  OK      ocp-ai-master01.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-4  0/3A026238   Standby (file based)  OK      ocp-ai-master03.calix.local

Recovery steps:
1. Patched cluster status to set db-2 as primary:
   oc patch cluster pai-apps-db -n pai-prod --type merge --subresource status -p '{"status":{"currentPrimary":"pai-apps-db-2","targetPrimary":"pai-apps-db-2"}}'

2. That wasn't enough — CNPG still configured db-2 as standby via override.conf. Found it:
   oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- cat /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata/override.conf

   What override.conf looks like when CNPG is treating the instance as a standby (this is the problem):
     primary_conninfo = 'host=pai-apps-db-rw user=streaming_replica port=5432 ...'
     primary_slot_name = '_cnpg_pai_apps_db_2'
     recovery_target_timeline = 'latest'
     restore_command = '/controller/manager wal-restore --log-destination /controller/log/postgres.json %f %p'

   The restore_command is what pulls WAL from MinIO. primary_conninfo points to pai-apps-db-rw (itself, but it can't connect because it hasn't started yet). This is why the instance loops.

3. Renamed the bad WAL archive in MinIO:
   oc exec minio-85b4477cdc-t275f -n pai-prod -- mv /data/cnpg-backups/pai-prod/pai-apps-db/wals /data/cnpg-backups/pai-prod/pai-apps-db/wals.bak

4. Forced WAL reset on db-2 (had to catch it while container was running):
   while ! oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- pg_resetwal -f /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata 2>/dev/null; do echo "waiting..."; sleep 2; done

5. db-2 came up as primary, db-1 reconnected as standby
6. db-3 was also stuck — stopped postgres, but container died before pg_resetwal could run. Deleted PVC and pod, CNPG rebuilt it as db-4 via pg_basebackup from db-2.

Key commands for CNPG troubleshooting:
kubectl cnpg status pai-apps-db -n pai-prod
kubectl cnpg hibernate on pai-apps-db -n pai-prod
kubectl cnpg hibernate off pai-apps-db -n pai-prod
kubectl cnpg promote pai-apps-db <instance> -n pai-prod






Impact Assessment — OCP-AI Cluster (EOSM-43606, April 11)
The OCP-AI cluster has dual-fabric redundancy across N9K-005 and N9K-006. Storage bonds on masters (bnd0 = eno7 + eno8, active-backup) and GPU workers (bond0, LACP 100Gbps) each have one leg per Nexus. As long as the switches are upgraded one at a time, storage and app VLAN traffic (1792-1798) will fail over to the surviving link with only a few seconds of disruption. Running workloads, MetalLB LB services (MinIO, Milvus, PostgreSQL), and GPU jobs will stay up.
The one gap is the management network. The master nodes currently run on a single management NIC (eno5, Fabric A only) — the Fabric B standby (eno6) is disabled to work around a MetalLB ARP conflict. That means while N9K-005 is rebooting, the API VIP (10.172.248.155) and Ingress VIP (10.172.248.156) will be unreachable. No oc CLI, no web console, no ArgoCD syncs during that window. Everything comes back as soon as N9K-005 is back online.
The other thing to watch is CloudNativePG. I ran into this last night during the MachineConfig rollout — MCO drained master01, CNPG auto-triggered a PostgreSQL switchover from db-1 to db-2, and the switchover got stuck. db-2 couldn't promote because it was trying to replay WAL files from MinIO that belonged to a different database instance (system identifier mismatch). All three DB pods ended up stuck, which took down auth-service and it-service-desk-agent in pai-prod. Had to manually reset the WAL and force db-2 to start as primary to recover. That was from a single node drain — a network disruption hitting multiple nodes at once could be worse. Plan is to hibernate the CNPG clusters before the window and wake them after to avoid a repeat.
Pre-maintenance: confirm rolling upgrade (not both switches at once), hibernate CNPG clusters, notify users about intermittent console/CLI access.
Post-maintenance: verify all nodes Ready, all cluster operators healthy, wake CNPG clusters, validate LB services with nc.


